<TEXT>
one year after iran and iraq agreed to a 
ceasefire in their eightyear war they have failed to sign a peace 
treaty and are rearming 
peace talks that began five days after the ceasefire went into 
effect aug 20 1988 have stalled representatives of the nations 
have not met face to face and there has been no progress in four 
rounds of negotiations through un representatives 
there have been moves to resume the talks in october but 
diplomats say there is little prospect of a breakthrough 
the talks have reached a standstill in disputes over the 
shattalarab waterway the southern border between the two 
countries and iraqs occupation of 1000 square miles of iranian 
territory even though the un ceasefire resolution specified a 
return to prewar borders 
the iraqis have claimed that political divisions in tehran 
blocked progress 
the june 3 death of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini and the election 
of president hashemi rafsanjani on july 28 raised hopes that talks 
would move ahead 
rafsanjani was instrumental in convincing khomeini to accept the 
un security councils ceasefire resolution following a series of 
battlefield defeats 
if rafsanjanis views prevail it could lead to some advance in 
the peace process but theres a lot of skepticism as to whether any 
formal peace treaty will ever be signed said philip robbins an 
analyst with londons royal institute for international affairs 
rafsanjani leader of irans socalled pragmatists declared when 
he was sworn in thursday that iran must try to stop the outbreak 
of war so it can concentrate on the massive task of postwar 
reconstruction 
but he has said iran will not make concessions in peace talks 
unless iraq withdraws from iranian territory 
iraq says there can be no progress until iran allows the 
shattalarab its main outlet to the persian gulf to be reopened 
baghdad says that shortly before it invaded iran on sept 22 
1980 it abrogated a 1975 agreement that drew the border down the 
middle of the waterway 
until then the border had run down the eastern iranian bank 
tehran says the agreement is still valid 
because the peace talks have stalled both nations continue to 
hold an estimated 100000 prisoners of war only a few hundred sick 
and disabled pows have been exchanged 
meanwhile iran and iraq are working hard to replenish their 
arsenals 
the iraqis retain the technological edge they had during the war 
and are likely to maintain it for at least five years as they 
upgrade their soviet and french weapons 
the iranians are replacing their increasingly deteriorating 
ussupplied arsenal with sovietdesigned systems a move analysts 
say will take years to complete 
robbins said that a key factor in whether both sides work toward 
a peace settlement will be the quality of weapons iran acquires 
the iraqis will be very nervous if the qualitative military gap 
is narrowed by the iranians if not accompanied by a formal peace 
settlement he said in a telephone interview 
iran and iraq want advanced technology to develop their own arms 
industries and lessen their dependence on other countries 
iran is believed to have a 20 billion military shopping list and 
is looking to the soviet bloc china and north korea for purchases 
a spate of ceasefire violations mainly by the iranians have 
further poisoned the atmosphere 
the iranians have flooded a large area held by the iraqis in the 
south seeking to force them back across the border 
that tactic has touched off several serious artillery clashes 
along the truce line where opposing forces are only yards apart in 
some places 
a un force has contained these confrontations but observers in 
baghdad have reported a recent increase in violations 
about 1 million people were killed in the eight years of fighting 
and un observers do not believe either side wants a fullscale 
resumption of the war however the observers fear skirmishes could 
easily escalate 
iran and iraq are rebuilding their ravaged cities and towns along 
the border repairing damaged oil installations and constructing new 
factories 
iran desperately needs stability to revitalize its sagging 
economy and carry out reconstruction 
political analysts believe rafsanjani may face challenges from 
irans radicals many of whom opposed the ceasefire and cannot 
afford to move too quickly on any issue that could antagonize them 
president saddam hussein of iraq on the other hand emerged from 
the war firmly entrenched in power his grip strengthened by the 
lightning offensives of early 1988 that drove the demoralized 
iranians out of the iraqi territory they held 
</TEXT>
