<TEXT>
the justice department eager to bring 
colombian drug dealers to trial in the united states is issuing a 
most wanted list of the top 12 and president bush today said 
such extraditions should go forward 
a us government plane has been in colombia since the weekend 
an administration source said today but theres no indication that 
it will be used to transport anybody who might be extradited to the 
united states 
the list released tuesday includes a dozen alleged top drug 
traffickers including leaders of the two major colombian cocaine 
cartels and a former colombian police officer who officials say 
tried to kill two us agents 
we dont know the whereabouts of any of these individuals 
attorney general dick thornburgh said noting that the government is 
enlisting the aid of the colombian government and interpol to bring 
them to justice here 
the interpol network of worldwide law enforcement agencies was 
alerted in recognition of the possibility that the suspects may 
have already fled colombia because of the recent crackdown on drug 
traffickers there thornburgh said 
asked today on cbs this morning why the colombian drug lords 
should not be tried in their own country thornburgh said 
in an ideal world they would be but as weve seen the tragic 
events there that have involved the assassination of judges law 
enforcement officials even a presidential candidate over the 
weekend have really robbed colombian officials of the ability to 
enforce their own laws 
about 80 alleged colombian drug traffickers have been indicted in 
the united states but their cases have languished since the 
colombian supreme court overturned its extradition treaty with the 
united states in 1987 
colombian president virgilio barco prompted by last weeks 
assassination of presidential candidate luis carlos galan 
instituted emergency measures to allow the immediate resumption of 
extraditions 
galan was an outspoken foe of drug traffickers 
bush at a news conferenece in kennebunkport maine where he is 
on vacation praised barcos efforts saying i have great respect 
for what president barco is trying to do i am convinced he is 
determined to whip the problem to beat it 
the process of extraditing drug trafficking suspects to the 
united states should go forward bush said 
the most wanted list does not include the one alleged 
medellin cartel moneylaunderer who was arrested over the weekend in 
colombia eduardo martinez romero 
we are taking steps to provide the necessary documentation to 
secure his extradition to the united states thornburgh said 
an administration source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said today that a us government plane has been in colombia since 
last weekend but its purpose there was unclear 
it could be used to transport martinez back to the united states 
the source said but there is no indication that it will be used for 
that purpose 
a source at the international airport in bogota identified the 
plane as belonging to the us drug enforcement administration but 
dea officials in washington declined comment 
the marshals service usually transports those being extradited to 
the united states and it has its own fleet of two 727s and a 
dozen or more smaller aircraft that can be used for such work 
said service spokesman bill dempsey 
we havent been brought into the picture yet on the martinez 
case dempsey said 
on tuesday thornburghs chief of staff robert ross said it was 
not clear how long the extradition of martinez might take 
the quickest thing that could happen is they could put somebody 
on a plane and deliver him to the united states or they could 
engage in some other process which could well involve us supplying 
different kinds of documentation which traditionally is what happens 
under extradition treaties ross said whether theyre going to 
operate that way or not we dont know 
the attorney general said the united states should not bow to 
fears that it might become targeted by the violence that has plagued 
colombia where dozens of judges and hundreds of law enforcement 
officers have been killed by drug traffickers 
we cant succumb in this country to what has already brought 
the criminal justice system to its knees in colombia he said 
they are rising from their knees they are standing up to these 
drug traffickers and they deserve every bit of support that we can 
give them and that support will be forthcoming 
those on the dozen most wanted are 
the three reputed medellin cartel leaders pablo emilio escobar 
gaviria 39 jorge luis ochoa vasquez 40 and jose gonzalo 
rodriguez gacha 42 
two of ochoa vasquezs brothers fabio 32 and juan david 41 
along with gustavo de jesus gaviria rivero 42 and gerardo moncada 
42 all are alleged members of the medellin cartel 
jose ivan duarte acero 37 a former police officer alleged to 
work with the medellin cartel drug enforcement administration 
spokesman con dougherty said acero was the gunman responsible for 
the attempted murder of two of our agents down there 
the reputed leaders of the cali cartel gilberto jose rodriguez 
orjuela 50 miguel angel rodriguez orjuela 45 and jose santacruz 
londono 45 also on the list is alleged cali cartel member jamie 
raul orjuela caballero 46 
