<TEXT>
while congress fiddles with defense budget 
cuts soviet president mikhail s gorbachev is building a more 
dangerous strategic arsenal despite his attentiongetting offers 
to slash military spending defense secretary dick cheney said 
wednesday 
the soviet union has been making major improvements to every 
leg of its strategic arsenal cheney said in systems ranging 
from intercontinental missiles and bombers to submarines and 
strategic defense the soviet union is getting stronger while our 
congress debates and our country treads water 
despite some cuts he said the soviets may well be producing a 
leaner and meaner military force and not just a smaller one 
he made the remarks in an address prepared for delivery to the 
veterans of foreign wars national convention in las vegas nev a 
text was made available at the pentagon 
cheney in some of his harshest criticism to date against his 
former colleagues lambasted the house for its budgetslashing 
approach to president bushs pentagon spending plan for the 1990 
fiscal year 
the former wyoming congressman accused the house of gutting the 
administrations military requests and using the defense budget as 
a jobs program 
cheney faulted the houses decision to limit production of the 
b2 stealth bomber carve 18 billion from the strategic defense 
initiative slash the mx rail garrison system and delete 100 
million for the midgetman missile from the budget 
the house and senate will meet in early september to craft a 
final blueprint on 295 billion in pentagon spending cheney warned 
that if the two chambers produce similar decisions in their upcoming 
conference the bill will be veto bait for the president 
he charged that many in the house seem to think there is no 
real threat anymore from the soviets 
they have seen some changes and apparently believe that 
everything now is just fine its as if they decided to give away 
their overcoats on the first sunny day in january he said 
while cheneys tone offered a contrast to the current climate of 
improved ussoviet relations he did note that the recently 
improved ussoviet ties paved the way for the inf treaty banning 
intermediate nuclear weapons in europe talks on slashing the 
superpowers strategic weapons and discussion on cutting 
conventional forces in europe 
but he said he could not say there was a reduced soviet threat 
if anything the united states is facing a more formidable 
offensive strategic arsenal today than before mr gorbachev took 
power thats right i said more formidable not less cheney said 
although there has been talk of a 14 percent cut in its defense 
budget since 1985 soviet defense expenditures have actually 
increased by an average of 3 percent per year in real terms at the 
same time our defense spending has declined in real terms by over 
11 percent cheney said 
as evidence of the heightened threat the pentagon chief pointed 
to the soviets 170 mobile ss25 singlewarhead intercontinental 
nuclear missiles their 58 ss24 missiles each of which carries 10 
independently targetable nuclear warheads and their modernization 
program for their 300 ss18 missiles which also carry 10 warheads 
however friendly mr gorbachev may sound however friendly he 
may in some respects wish to be he cannot explain the deployment of 
the beefedup ss18 as a friendly act cheney said 
the secretary called for a tough us response to the soviet 
program saying we need to modernize our own strategic forces 
because soviet strategic capabilities are becoming more dangerous 
under mr gorbachev despite his popular impression to the 
contrary 
cheney called for restoration of the presidents budget requests 
in order to respond adequately to the soviet threat 
the soviets are moving forward it would be irresponsible for 
the united states to try to get by with aging systems cheney said 
a study by the cia and the pentagons defense intelligence agency 
issued in april reported that soviet defense spending rose 3 percent 
last year despite gorbachevs promises to cut his military budget 
the study added however that it appeared gorbachev was laying 
the groundwork for his proposed 142 percent cut in defense spending 
