<TEXT>
diana vreeland who reigned over the world of 
haute couture for more than three decades creating trends and 
coining the term beautiful people was mourned wednesday as a 
fashion original 
she was and remains the only genious fashion editor said 
photographer richard avedon who worked with mrs vreeland when she 
edited harpers bazaar and then vogue 
mrs vreeland died tuesday at lenox hill hospital she had been 
in failing health for several years she was believed to be about 86 
years old but her age remained a mystery whatever age you are 
youre older than you ought to be she once said 
mrs vreeland became a fashion high priestess whose power was 
matched by her biting wit and sense of the provocative 
she popularized the turtleneck sweater discovered the designer 
halston and was the first to see jacqueline kennedys potential as a 
fashion force she could also be outlandish advising readers to 
turn their old fur coats into bathrobes and wash their blond 
childrens hair in dead champagne 
vreeland aphorisms like the bikini is only the most important 
invention since the atomic bomb were as legendary as her barbs 
she once called diva maria callas table manners as common as 
mud and said coco chanel had the expression of a baby bull 
dressed like a prussian sailor 
she was born diana dalziel into a world of glitter and privilege 
in paris at the turn of the century 
in 1914 her parents scottish banker frederick young dalziel and 
emily key dalziel came to the united states to escape world war i 
and set up their household here 
mrs vreeland had little formal education a few months at 
prestigious private schools she studied ballet with russian 
choreographer michel fokine and learned to ride horses from william 
buffalo bill cody during summers in wyoming 
in 1923 she met thomas reed vreeland a yale graduate banker 
and impeccable dresser whom she married the following year he died 
in 1966 the couple had two children thomas reed jr and frederick 
d the vreelands moved to london where she traveled and met such 
notables as evelyn waugh and cole porter and continued her interest 
in dancing by becoming a member of the tiller girls a chorus line 
used by florenz ziegfeld 
when the couple returned to new york in 1936 mrs vreeland 
supplemented her husbands income by working for harpers bazaar 
over the years mrs vreelands influence in the fashion world 
became immense and in 1962 she left harpers to join its archrival 
vogue a year later she became its editor in chief 
at vogue mrs vreeland shaped the look of what she called the 
1960s youthquake featuring such unconventional models as marisa 
berenson twiggy and baby jane holzer 
her beautiful people or bps included people of royalty and 
wealth her favorite fashions included seethrough tops pants for 
women costume jewelry and the peasant look 
in 1971 mrs vreeland was fired from vogue when the publisher 
conde nast decided the time had come for a new editor 
she became a special consultant to the costume institute of the 
metropolitan museum of art where she organized shows on parisian 
originals of the early 1900s and hollywood glamour styles of the 
1930s 40s and 50s 
a striking figure who wore her black hair swept back severely 
mrs vreeland had a penchant for tstrap shoes and cashmere sweaters 
that precisely matched her skirts the color red that pervaded her 
park avenue apartment added to an aura of eccentricity 
truman capote called her one of the very few great original 
women 
the story is told that at lunch one day at a wellknown 
restuarant mrs vreeland responded to seeing a cockroach on her 
table by leaping up and singing la cucaracha 
she encouraged the telling of such extravagant anecdotes saying 
i need a lot of fanfare no question about it 
she is survived by her sons four grandchildren and four 
greatgrandchildren funeral plans were private a public memorial 
service was planned for the fall 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

