<TEXT>
the advisory committee on federal pay says 
government workers should be given a pay increase of 10 percent next 
year to help narrow the gap between their salaries and those paid to 
counterparts in the private sector 
the bottom line on federal pay is that the gap has become a 
canyon said martin l duggan the committees chairman in 
releasing its latest annual report 
he pointed to figures issued two weeks ago by the presidents pay 
agent an interagency group involving officials of the labor 
department office of personnel management and office of management 
and budget showing that the pay gap has now grown to 286 percent 
duggan said that we commend the president and congress for 
granting a 36 percent increase to become effective in january 1990 
but the committee believes that an additional 64 percent is 
needed 
this would send a strong and clear message to young people who 
would not consider a public service career that the government is 
serious about recruiting wellqualified people he said in issuing 
the report tuesday 
duggan added that the absence of adequate pay increases over 
the past decade is driving out the capable people who are already in 
the federal government 
in addition to the pay raise recommendation the panels report 
calls for phasing in further increases to remove the pay gap over a 
fouryear period reforming the pay system by making salaries more 
responsive to labor market conditions redesigning the health care 
benefit program to provide more costefficient coverage and 
updating the governments benefits package to better compete for 
skills in the labor market 
carol a bonosaro president of the senior executives 
association representing top career federal executives called the 
advisory committees report right on target in urging the pay 
increase 
she noted that the pay gap tends to be greater at upper levels of 
government service with gs15s falling 367 percent behind their 
private sector counterparts 
this is even more strong evidence that senior federal 
executives above that level are grossly undercompensated ms 
bonosaro said 
john n sturdivant president of the american federation of 
government employees aflcio commented that as a result of the 
continued imposition of pay caps beginning in 1978 the federal 
government has found itself in an untenable position with inferior 
noncompetitive salaries in a nationally tight labor market 
failure to begin to remedy the current pay gap will virtually 
ensure that the nations largest employer will remain the employer 
of last resort sturdivant said 
afge is the largest union for government workers representing 
700000 federal employees in the united states and overseas 
