<TEXT>
the national wildlife federation escalating 
the legal fight over protecting endangered sea turtles from the nets 
of gulf coast shrimp fisherman took its case to a federal appeals 
court wednesday 
rebuffed by a us district court judge on tuesday the 
federation asked the us court of appeals to reinstate a law that 
requires shrimpers to use devices that let turtles escape from their 
nets 
the federation sought an emergency injunction to ensure the 
continued survival of the severely endangered kemps ridley sea 
turtle and four other sea turtle species listed as threatened or 
endangered 
the federation is challenging commerce secretary robert 
mosbachers decision allowing shrimpers to limit trawling time to 
105 minutes in lieu of turtle excluder devices or teds 
under the 105minute limit shrimpers can have their nets in the 
water for 90 minutes the length of time some officials claim a sea 
turtle can survive while submerged the regulations give shrimpers 
another 7 minutes to get their nets in the water and 7 minutes to 
remove them 
mosbacher suspended enforcement of the teds regulations july 24 
after a weekend of protests by shrimpers who claim the devices 
reduce their catch and threaten their livelihood 
according to the biological opinion of the secretarys own 
scientists the substitution of a limited tow time for required ted 
use in the midst of the shrimping season will result in the deaths 
of thousands of threatened and endangered sea turtles in the gulf 
and the atlantic the federation said in its appeal 
the temporary regulations drafted under a court order by us 
district judge thomas hogan are in effect through sept 8 when 
mosbacher must issue final rules 
mosbacher issued the temporary regulations after the wildlife 
federation filed suit and hogan ruled the turtles were being left 
totally unprotected 
but federation claims that national marine fisheries service 
scientists have concluded the 105minute plan will jeopardize the 
continued existence of five threatened and endangered species of sea 
turtles 
commerce spokesman brian gorman said the final rules due out 
sept 8 are still under consideration 
