<TEXT>
dry beer is becoming a big hit across the united 
states although most drinkers still have no idea what it is or what 
it tastes like 
that may be one reason the distinct new beer has become so 
popular 
the curiosity level is unbelievable said bob goughenour a 
group brand executive at anheuserbusch inc who helped bring dry 
beer to american supermarkets and taverns 
so be prepared 
the cacophonous vendors at the stadium may soon begin asking 
hows about a nice dry one your neighbor may invite you over 
for something dry to drink 
its been a year since anheuserbusch introduced michelob dry in 
this country and the brand has been so successful at one point 
the brewer couldnt make it fast enough to keep up with sales the 
company earlier this year introduced a dry version of budweiser the 
worlds bestselling beer 
bud dry should be available nationally by the end of the year 
said goughenour 
were just delighted with dry beer our volumes are more than 
twice what we expected its just been incredible he said 
dry beer is brewed to produce a lesssweet taste that doesnt 
linger its made with a process that converts more of the malt and 
rice into fermentable sugars which interact more efficiently with 
the yeast 
the beer contains less sugar than regular beer fewer calories 
and no aftertaste which probably is its most noticeable difference 
bud drys advertising slogan is comes on strong then its 
gone 
last year about 500000 to 600000 barrels of dry beer were sold 
in the united states said frank walters director of research for 
impact magazine a new yorkbased trade publication for the 
alcoholic beverage industry 
this year walters expects sales of about 25 million barrels 
next year he said the amount should climb to 6 million barrels 
annual sales of beer in the united states total about 188 million 
barrels 
its still very early to say but we expect by the end of this 
century dry beer should be at about 20 million barrels walters 
said but this category is so new that that could all change in 
the next hour 
one big question remains about dry beer is it just a fad 
its honestly too early to tell said robert weinberg an 
industry consultant and professor of marketing management at 
washington university in st louis i think it may be more than a 
fad because it looks like this is a very pleasing product to young 
women 
weinberg said several female students have told him they like 
michelob dry because its the only beer that doesnt make them feel 
like they smell like a brewery 
the female market has been something brewers have hungrily eyed 
for decades weinberg said and if dry beer opens the door to that 
market it will prove much more than a fad 
odds that a beer drinker will be male are about twotoone 
weinberg said 
at the countrys second largest brewery miller brewing co 
officials are carefully watching the growth of dry beer but remain 
unconvinced that the category will be around for a long time 
our research shows that these products do not offer any 
significant benefit or appeal to mainstream beer drinkers said 
miller spokeswoman susan henderson 
she said miller based in milwaukee has no plans to plunge into 
the dry beer fray 
nineteen imported and domestic dry beers are currently sold 
around the country including canadian japanese and european brands 
g heileman brewing co of lacrosse wis sells five different 
dry beers on a regional basis including rainier special dry in the 
northwest and ic special dry in pennsylvania 
earlier this month the company which is a collection of 
regional breweries introduced lone star dry in texas said 
spokesman bill eiler 
we see a real strong future in dry beer we think its here to 
stay eiler said 
although its just started to catch the publics fancy dry beer 
is not new 
regional beers in the 1950s and 60s such as rheingold and stag 
pale dry were touted for dry taste but they never caused a big a 
stir in the industry like the current craze which got started about 
two years ago in japan 
asahi breweries ltd of toyko introduced a dry brand that started 
the sensation and prompted all of japans major brewers to scramble 
to concoct their own dry brands 
now the category has captured 20 percent to 30 percent of the 
japanese beer market industry analysts say 
goughenour was sent to japan by anheuserbusch to investigate the 
skyrocketing dry beer sales and see if the company should get into 
the category 
he came back perplexed 
i couldnt figure out how this could be applied in this 
country that was the question mark he said when we first 
started nobody knew what we were talking about americans know dry 
wine they know dry martinis and dry cleaning but they really dont 
know what dry is 
in japan consumers know what dry is because dry sake is a staple 
beverage so dry beer is kind of a logical extension for them 
goughenour said 
but in the united states the concept of dry is elusive 
thats why goughenour spent a lot of time asking us beer 
drinkers to define the meaning of dry as they thought it might 
apply to beer 
we got consumers to tell us what dry is and then we made 
something with a brand new refreshing smooth taste he said 
they told us what to make 
</TEXT>
