copper futures prices rallied strongly wednesday on new yorks 
commodity exchange amid fears that the shutdown of mexicos largest 
copper mine would put another crimp in the already tight supplies of 
the metal 
on other markets precious metal futures retreated most oil 
futures advanced grains and soybeans were mostly lower and 
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher 
copper futures settled 245 cents to 255 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in september at 12785 a pound the highest 
settlement for a copper contract since may 5 the september contract 
traded as high as 12920 during the session 
the mexican government declared its cananea copper mine bankrupt 
over the weekend and shut it down prompting speculation that the 
mine could be closed for several months 
the mine is capable of producing about 160000 metric tons of 
refined copper a year about 2 percent of the world total 
copper prices have risen sharply this month underpinned by an 
ongoing nationwide copper miners strike in peru a strike at a 
highland valley copper co mine in canada and persistent production 
problems in several other major copperproducing countries 
the market will look at any situation that tells us about 
supply said craig sloane an analyst with smith barney harris 
upham amp co in new york if the situation in mexico means theres 
a potential loss of supply thats important 
gold and silver futures slid lower on the comex partly in 
reaction to the dollars gains against other major currencies 
